04126nam a22005415i 9780773597044DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735970447 a10.1515/97807735970442doi  a(DE-B1597)654880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR448.S44bS54 2015eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/3532231 aSigler, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSexual Enjoyment in British Romanticism :bGender and Psychoanalysis, 1753-1835 /cDavid Sigler. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Literary Gender Debates and Their Relation to the Unconscious -- t“It is Unaccountable”: Anxiety and the Cause of Desire in Pride and Prejudice -- tDead Faith and Contraband Goods: Joanna Southcott and the Logic of Sexuation -- tBrotherly Love and Two Masquerades in Mary Robinson’s Walsingham -- tMasochism and Psychoanalysis in Zofloya, or the Moor -- tPercy Bysshe Shelley’s Zastrozzi and the Psychoanalytic Act -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDebates about gender in the British Romantic period often invoked the idea of sexual enjoyment: there was a broad cultural concern about jouissance, the all-engulfing pleasure pertaining to sexual gratification. On one hand, these debates made possible the modern psychological concept of the unconscious - since desire was seen as an uncontrollable force, the unconscious became the repository of disavowed enjoyment and the reason for sexual difference. On the other hand, the tighter regulation of sexual enjoyment made possible a vast expansion of the limits of imaginable sexuality. In Sexual Enjoyment and British Romanticism, David Sigler shows how literary writers could resist narrowing gender categories by imagining unregulated enjoyment. As some of the era's most prominent thinkers - including Edmund Burke, Mary Wollstonecraft, Mary Robinson, Joanna Southcott, Charlotte Dacre, Jane Austen, and Percy Bysshe Shelley - struggled to understand sexual enjoyment, they were able to devise new pleasures in a time of narrowing sexual possibilities. Placing Romantic-era literature in conversation with Lacanian psychoanalytic theory, Sexual Enjoyment in British Romanticism reveals the fictive structure of modern sexuality, makes visible the diversity of sexual identities from the period, and offers a new understanding of gender in British Romanticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPsychoanalysis in literature. 0aRomanticismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aRomanticismzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex (Psychology) in literature. 0aSexzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aSexzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359704440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597044/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles